&PARAM_PREBOLAM
 INPUT_FORMAT='INPUT_DATA', INPUT_FILE_STD=MHF_STD,
 NLON=NPOINTX, NLAT=NPOINTY, NLEV=NLEVATM,
 DLON=DX, DLAT=DY,
 X0D=X0ROT, Y0D=Y0ROT,
 ALON0=X1V, ALAT0=Y1V, P0=100000., ALFA=1.00,
 SOIL_LEV0=  0.05, 0.13, 0.32, 0.69, 1.30, 2.21, 3.48, 5.17, 7.34, 10.05, 13.36, 17.33, 22.02,
 -9999., -9999., -9999., -9999., -9999., -9999., -9999.,
 NLEV_ATM_INP_MAX=200, NLEV_SOIL_INP_MAX=15,
 NIST=01, INST_START=01, NSFC=0
&END

----------------  PARAMETERS OF THE (OUTPUT) BOLAM MODEL GRID  ----------------------

NLON, NLAT, NLEV: Dimensions of the (rotated) BOLAM grid.
NLEVG:            Number of soil levels.
DLON, DLAT:       Resolution in degrees.
X0D, Y0D:         Geographical coordinates in deg. of the centre of rotation
                  (normally near the centre of the model grid).
                  If the input model grid is in rotated coordinates (for ex. IFS or BOLAM),
                  then the nested domain must be rotated, with the same rotation centre.
                  For non rotated grid, define X0D=Y0D=0.
ALON0, ALAT0:     Rotated coordinates in deg of the SW corner (point "v") of the BOLAM grid.
                  In case of non rotated grid, ALON0, ALAT0 define the true coordinates of the SW corner;
                  DLON should be set to DLAT/COS(lat0), where lat0 is a mean latitude of the model grid.
P0                Reference pressure defining the hybrid vertical coordinate.
ALFA:             Exponent defining the hybrid vertical coordinate over mountains - acceptable values:
                  .8 < ALFA < 1.5 (low values are better but may not be compatible with high mountains).
SLT1...:          Model soil layers thickness (m).

----------------  PARAMETERS OF THE INPUT DATA GRID  ----------------------

INPUT_FORMAT:      'grib2' for NOAA-GFS and ECMWF-IFS input data;
                   'mhfb' for Bolam or Globo (CNR-ISAC) models input data.
NLEV_ATM_INP_MAX:  Max. possible number of atmospheric levels of the input data.
NLEV_SOIL_INP_MAX: Max. possible number of soil levels of the input data.
INPUT_FILE_STD:    used only for INPUT_FORMAT='mhfb', denotes type of the input data:
                   1 - united file (all instants in the same file),
                   2 - separated files (one file for each instant).
NIST:              Number of instants present in input data (total of analysis + forecasts);
                   for INPUT_FORMAT='mhfb' and INPUT_FILE_STD=1: last instant number present
                   in input data to be processed.
INST_START:        For INPUT_FORMAT='mhfb' and INPUT_FILE_STD=1: progressive instant
                   number in input data to be used as initial condition.
NSFC:              Flag (0 or 1) for surface parameters (soil, snow depth, etc.)
                   If surface data are available at first instant only, NSFC=1, otherwise NSFC=0.
